have been having some interesting conversations with people on twitter about the use cases of doing AI on-chain. I was wondering if is any Bittensor content regarding this I could consume?

In my mind, I see a massive opportunity for Bittensor to become a true non-profit open source replacement to OpenAI... but i am also interested to explore the applicability for commercial use case, and thus especially interested in discussions around the seemingly public nature of both the data and model output when being on-chain. For example, how this transparency would be handled for commercial entities (esp regarding regulations like GDPR, commercially sensitive data, ownership, etc).

someone mentioned "My understanding is that the data is not necessarily public - datasets can remain "siloed", but accessible. I'm not 100% sure on that though". If so, i'd be very keen to learn about this. Would this require private permissioned miner subnets or something?

thanks in advance.
You likely wouldn't use bittensor for something private like that. But theoretically we could have a subnet were everyone runs homomorphic encryption-compatible models
But I think research on that is very limited as it's quite hard to do
thanks for the response! okay, so would you say the primary use case of Bittensor is for public common-good AI models?
You need stake to access any of the models on the network, so I wouldn't say free as in beer, but it's fairly open

ah, so the ledger is not public, only for those who hold TAO?

sort of like Wikipedia, but you need $wiki to read/write access the website?
the ledger?
The AI is not done on-chain
The ranking and incentivization calculations are done on-chain
but the evaluation, requests, and responses are all done off-chain
The idea is you need some stake to incentivize a model to give you a response
And with enough stake, you can push the network towards any task you want
ah okay, i thought as part of the ranking/incentivisation each miner would need to publish their output, or at least it could be inferred.
but still you need TAO to access the network of what is being trained, and see the results?
is the front end intended to publicize what the network is doing? or is there some obfuscation, and only really the miners that were involved have access to the data and output?

the blockchain is for the incentive layer (btc style tokenomics) to incentivize the miners and validators to produce intelligence--it's a "market for intelligence," basically. To gain access to the network's intelligence, you need a validator, or a tool built on a validator, as I understand it.

I was explaining this to someone yesterday and realized I wasn't quite sure how these two things balanced/overlapped: influencing the network towards specific tasks as a validator, while also being incentivized by tao to rank miners in a way that agrees with the majority of validators (you're penalized for being an outlier right?). Would love to understand better how incentivizing forces like this will overlap, its one of the most interesting aspects of the network imo
The more TAO you have staked (as a proportion of total stake), the less you need to worry about the other stake
and also, you are effectively "paying"  for the change in task
by your loss of divs for being out-of-consensus

so normally, a validator seeks to achieve consensus, which is good for divs, but if the vali wants to use the network for specific tasks (& thereby incentivize miners to do specific things), it will fall out of consensus & thereby decrease divs? (Sorry if this is :Smooooth: , just trying to wrap my head around it)
They don't have to rank that way to use if for different tasks, but if they want to incentivize the network for those tasks, they can
You can just send queries without setting weights on a peer
But by setting weights for a good response to your task, you are rewarding that peer
So they are incentivized to learn to do that task better
ohh ok this makes a lot of sense
yeah, super helpful as always, vune 🙏
given you had 51% (or more) of the stake, you could make the network do whatever task you wanted
Like say you got enough validators on-board
